title.narrative: MATERNAL, NEWBORN AND CHILD HEALTH

description.narrative: By 2025, Ministries of Health and partners have strengthened capacity to plan, deliver, monitor and report on quality maternal, neonatal, child and adolescent health and HIV services., which contributes to Fast-Track The End Of Hiv/Aids, Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being, Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Evaluations, Research And Data, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2025, more neonates, infants and children survive and thrive, and fewer women die during pregnancy and childbirth.

description.narrative: To strengthen maternal, neonatal, child, adolescent and HIV services in Somalia, UNICEF supported the implementation of essential package of health services (EPHS) in 43 districts and contributed to Prevention of Mother to Child Transmission (PMTCT) and antiretroviral therapy. A total of 986,126 people received curative care through the first OPD visit (including 577,606 children under five years of age), 54,665 women attended at least four antenatal care (ANC) visits,; 77,244 deliveries were supported by skilled birth attendant, and 121,245 infants received Penta 3 vaccinations. The updated DHIS2 will substantially improve planning, monitoring, and reporting in 2022. | Status:Met | As-of Date:17/12/2021
